
In JavaScript, Maps are a built-in data structure that allows you to store key-value pairs. Here's how you can work with them:
Creating a Map:
const myMap = new Map();

Adding Key-Value Pairs:
JavaScript

myMap.set("name", "John");
myMap.set("age", 30);
myMap.set(1, "One"); // Keys can be any data type

Retrieving Values:
JavaScript

console.log(myMap.get("name")); // Output: "John"
console.log(myMap.get(1)); // Output: "One"

Checking if a Key Exists:
JavaScript

console.log(myMap.has("name")); // Output: true
console.log(myMap.has("address")); // Output: false

Deleting a Key-Value Pair:
JavaScript

myMap.delete("age");


Iterating Over a Map:
JavaScript

for (const [key, value] of myMap) {
  console.log(key, value); // Output: "name John", "1 One"
}


Other Useful Methods:
myMap.size: Returns the number of key-value pairs.
myMap.clear(): Empties the map.



